snippet.textDisplay: Kirby represents the zenith of capitalistic hubris. He consumes everything, leaving nothing behind. In his wake, trails of nothingness—not even one dead body. The folly of the capitalist is exactly the same: once a product has been consumed it returns to nothingness. Can the toy you played with as a child, sitting in the dark recesses of your basement closet, truly be considered alive anymore? Or how about that book you picked up at the checkout line at Barnes and Noble? “Thus Spoke Zarathustra” or something like that? You don’t remember either—you just wanted to impress the cute cashier lady. But you get home, place the book on your bedside table and plan on doing some light reading before you go to bed. But you’ve never done light reading and you never will. Had you read that book, you would understand. You would understand Nietzsche was onto something. Perhaps God is actually dead after all. What God could allow Kirby, the manifestation of human greed in puffball form, to exist? He will continue to consume until a void of nothingness is all that remains. Are we really so different?

snippet.textDisplay: Kirby represents the mental state of the average person in the midst of playing an action game. The id, the part of our mind that directs our basic needs such as eating, sleeping, and jumping swiftly away from enemies who are trying to kill us, is given the front seat, while our more sophisticated faculties, such as our ability to pilot giant mechs, are relegated to a support role that isn't given a tremendous amount of focus.  Kirby is a vehicle for us.

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, I’ve made a discovery. August 2, 2019 was in between the almost 2 month haitus of Unraveled, so this was why there was such a long break between his BotW cooking video and his Pet HP video. Furthermore, the Pet HP video starts with Brian saying ‘Is life quantifiable?’ Which is clearly referencing his insanity over Kirby’s origin.

But wait, there’s more! January 15th also makes sense! This is because he was driven so insane not just by Kirby’s origin, but by his realisation that he is a Luigi and not a Waluigi. Assuming that in the UCU (Unraveled Cinematic Universe) Brian runs off after the release of the Waluigi video, around Christmas. Which gives him 3 weeks to build that beard and moustache.

Thank you for coming to my TED Talk.

Edit: Black holes are generally shaped as circles as well, since he is pretty much a natural phenomena that cannot be stopped, its natural for higher sentient beings to be afraid of him, since they may be able to tame him but not able to stop him. Him being pink doesn't matter since at the end of the day we see colors through eyes designed a certain way and other creatures may look at him and see different colors, also it could just be colorized just like when NASA put some colors on their pictures so its easier to understand (and pretty).

snippet.textDisplay:
Kirby's simplicity can be explained BY his power.

He has no need to evolve a long neck to reach his food; he simply inhales massively and his food comes to him.

He does not need side facing eyes like a deer, for what predator need he fear?

His skin is unblemished because it is both impenetrable and untouchable; no foe could hope to break his hide through mortal objects alone, and lives in fear of what horrifying truths they will bear witness to if they should ever make contact with his eldritch visage.

Kirby
Is a god.

snippet.textDisplay: Okay I get this is mostly a joke but if we think about his philosophically it’s common sense that beings with great amounts of power tend to not use their abilities to their fullest. Think of it from the point of the view of an artist; Someone who’s studies music can go down two different paths: someone who learns and ends up performing and being generic OR someone who is so close to music and understands all musical terminology on a university-graduate level but still plays and composes for themselves. In some people’s eyes, that may seem like a waste of talent, but one thing true greats realize is that they live for their craft. Look at the film “The Legend is 1900”. He could’ve left that ship, become a mega famous musician and made lots of money, but he didn’t. He stayed behind on the ship and, well, blew up with it. Kirby is just fucking stupid, but when related to reality, Kirby represents someone who lives for their craft, not for the benefit of society or something else.
